The 57-gross register ton,  crab-fishing vessel sank quickly off the northeast coast of Montague Island at the entrance to Prince William Sound on the south-central coast of Alaska after striking an unidentified object. Her crew of three reached shore in a life raft.

The bulk carrier disappeared in the North Pacific Ocean  south of Kodiak Island and  south of Kodiak, Alaska, with the loss of her entire crew of 30 South Korean nationals. Searchers found only four overturned lifeboats, some debris, and an oil slick.

The fishing vessel/cargo ship was destroyed in a fire in Langevåg, Norway. Wreck scrapped in Trondheim, Norway in May 1975.

The  purse seine fishing vessel sank in Peril Strait in the Alexander Archipelago in Southeast Alaska,  south of Juneau, Alaska, with the loss of two lives. Her lone survivor, her captain, was rescued from the water by a helicopter.

The cabin cruiser sank when a wave capsized it after its engine failed in the Indian Ocean off Lourenço Marques, Mozambique. Three of the four people on board drowned. The only survivor was a South African woman who swam  to safety on a buoy and reported that two dolphins protected her from sharks and helped her stay afloat when she tired during her swim.

The schooner was in collision with an unnamed weather ship  and sank with the loss of seven of her eleven crew.
The oil rig supply vessel foundered in the North Sea  west of the Vyl Lightship with the loss of nine of her nineteen crew.
